        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose to observe with ALMA in band 7 using the most extended 12m configuration. We opt for a standard representative band frequency of 336 GHz, yielding a resolution of 0.122 arcsec. We require a high resolution to maximise the source-to-background flux ratio within the beam; this requires us to observe in bands 7, 8 or 9. Neither bands 8 nor 9 are feasible due to long time requirements as a result of their atmospheric windows and higher calibration time. We cannot go to band 6 because we expect the disk flux to fall off fairly rapidly beyond $\sim$1mm, and hence risk observing at a non-optimal wavelength with significantly reduced disk flux. We therefore opt to observe in band 7, which lies at short enough wavelengths to still observe in the peak region of the disk flux, and which lies in an atmospheric window conducive to an efficient observation. 

We do not know the exact size of the disk in this system but we can make a reasonable estimate. Vicente \&amp; Alves (2005) found typical disk sizes in single star systems in the Orion Trapezium cluster to range from $\sim$50--194 AU. If we take their median disk size of 75 AU, then the flux from the disk begins to quickly fall off beyond $\sim$1mm. Making the assumption that the circumbinary disk in this system is comparable in size to those in single star systems is reasonable because the two stars are very closely separated ($a = 11 R_{\odot}$), and hence the outer regions evolve as though there is only one central star. 

We estimate the disk flux by considering a razor thin disk that is aligned with the plane of the binary's orbit and which radiates away energy from both incident stellar flux and the gravitational potential energy released by the accretion of gas (estimated as $\dot{M} = 10^{-11} M_{\odot}$\,yr$^{-1}$ from the H$\alpha$ profile and UV excess). The disk's SED is shown in Figure \ref{sed} by the brown dot-dashed line. In this model we have set the disk outer radius to 75 AU, which gives a flux within the beam of 0.092 mJy in band 7. We estimate the expected nebular flux in band 7 from the archival \emph{Spitzer} and \emph{Herschel} observations. We determine the flux in the pixel at the location of CoRoT 223992193 and scale by the number of beams in that pixel to achieve the estimated flux per beam. The nebular fluxes per beam are shown by the black points in Figure \ref{sed}.  We note that the data points cannot all be fit with single temperature blackbodies, suggesting a range of dust temperatures within the nebula. The SPIRE data appear mutually consistent and, in the ALMA band, the expected contribution will come from emission matching these data. We therefore fit these data with single temperature blackbody emission, with standard temperatures of 20 and 30 K, to predict the nebular flux in band 7. The average of these two predictions is 0.0026 mJy and we take this value for the nebular flux per beam. The actual observable nebular flux is probably less than this as we see evidence in the archival images for large-scale spatial variations in the nebula (see Figure \ref{sed}, right hand plot). These variations are larger than the maximum recoverable scale and so will not be seen by ALMA.
In addition. it is important to note that this observation is limited by the sensitivity required to detect the disk flux and not by the nebular emission.

With our proposed setup, taking the flux emitted by a disk with an outer radius of 75 AU, and requiring a signal-to-noise ratio (SNR) of 5, we estimate a total required time of 5.01 hours. We request a SNR of 5 as the predicted disk flux is an estimate. In case our estimate is slightly optimistic, aiming for a SNR of 5, will still allow us to achieve a SNR of 3 for a disk flux as low as 0.055mJy (in the same time). By detecting the disk we will be able to constrain the temperature of the disk material. Furthermore, we will achieve a spatial resolution of $\sim$95AU, which may enable us to resolve the disk itself.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
