    <prp:code/>
    <prp:abstract>We propose to use ALMA in band 7 to detect the first circumbinary disk around an eclipsing binary. We recently discovered CoRoT 223992193, a low-mass, close-separation, detached eclipsing binary in the NGC 2264 star forming region (~3 Myr), comprising two pre-main sequence M dwarfs, and showing indirect evidence for a circumbinary disk. The system's SED displays a mid-IR excess, which is too cool for circumstellar yet too hot for a circumbinary disk(s). We model this excess as emission from dust in the central cavity of a circumbinary disk and thereby infer the presence of such a disk, which would be required to replenish the material in the cavity. Unfortunately, we cannot obtain direct evidence for this disk from archival Spitzer/MIPS or Herschel/PACS &amp; SPIRE data due to strong background nebular emission. By observing the system at much higher spatial resolution with ALMA we hope to detect the disk. This would constitute the first confirmed discovery of a circumbinary disk in an eclipsing system, and would enable us to constrain the temperature of the disk material. Furthermore, we will achieve a spatial resolution of ~95 AU, which may enable us to resolve the disk itself.</prp:abstract>
